<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ambassador to Lebanon at the time of the Iran-Contra affair said he had no 
significant role in the scandal and was involved only in getting a freed 
hostage out of the country. Reginald Bartholomew told the Senate Foreign 
Relations Committee that he had no advance knowledge that U.S. arms were 
swapped for the freedom of the Rev. Benjamin Weir, an American hostage who was 
released Sept. 14, 1985. "My role was restricted to logistical arrangements, at 
the request of the National Security Council," to get Weir to safety as quickly 
as possible, Bartholomew said. Bartholomew has been nominated by President Bush 
to be undersecretary of state for security affairs, science and technology. 
</P>
