<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Residents of Beirut sought shelter in basements and bunkers during citywide 
shelling as five weeks of relentless battles touched off international appeals 
for a cease-fire. The rocket and artillery barrages slammed into the Christian 
and Muslim sectors during intensified fighting around the Lebanese capital 
between Christian army units and an alliance of Druze militia members and 
Syrian troops. Meanwhile, the United States, Kuwait, Jordan and Pope John Paul 
II appealed for a truce in what has become one of the bloodiest rounds of the 
14-year civil war. 
</P>
