<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST /LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: TEACHER CHARGED WITH STUDENT SEXUAL LIAISON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A San Fernando High School teacher has been charged with three counts of 
unlawful sexual intercourse with a 16-year-old female student, authorities said 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
Richard Shrake, 52, of Valencia was arrested April 4 after the student, who 
authorities said had willfully engaged in sex with Shrake, told a family member 
about their relationship, said Detective Gary Lyon of the Los Angeles Police 
Department's child abuse unit. 
</P>
<P>
"She confided in an older brother, and he convinced her to tell police," Lyon 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The incidents are alleged to have taken place between March, 1988, and March of 
this year at Shrake's former Reseda residence, his home in Valencia and in his 
car, Lyon said. The girl, now 17, attended San Fernando High but was not a 
student of Shrake's. 
</P>
<P>
"She was on an emotional downside when they first met, and he took advantage of 
that," Lyon said. The youth decided to tell her brother about her involvement 
with Shrake after "she realized she was being used." 
</P>
<P>
Diana Munatones, a spokeswoman for the Los Angeles Unified School District, 
said since his arrest, Shrake has been placed on compulsory leave of absence 
without pay pending the outcome of the case. 
</P>
<P>
Munatones said Shrake, who is not married, has been a special education teacher 
at San Fernando High since 1982 and has worked on and off for the school 
district for 22 years. 
</P>
<P>
Shrake is free on $10,000 bail and is scheduled to be arraigned in San Fernando 
Municipal Court on April 25. If convicted, he faces a maximum of six years in 
prison. 
</P>
