<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
U.S. URGED TO LIFT FETAL TISSUE BAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Expert advisers to the National Institutes of Health formally recommended today 
that the government lift its year-old ban on transplant research using tissue 
from aborted human fetuses. 
</P>
<P>
But researchers and federal officials said the ban is likely to remain in place 
for some time, despite the experts' recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
The ban stems from a proposed study on transplanting fetal nerve tissue into 
people suffering from Parkinson's disease. Due to the emotional nature of the 
debate over fetal tissue research and strong opposition from the anti-abortion 
movement, the panel's report is likely to undergo lengthy and intense scrutiny 
by Congress and the Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA041889-0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 45882 </DOCID>
<DATE>
