<P>
SKIER BILL JOHNSON HAS SURGERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DENVER 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Downhill racer Bill Johnson has undergone surgery for removal of a ruptured 
disk in his lower back and faces an extensive rehabilitation program. 
</P>
<P>
The surgery Monday at Denver's St. Anthony Central Hospital went "pretty well," 
according to Dr. Courtney Brown, who declined to speculate on Johnson's chances 
of returning to ski racing. "That's an impossible thing to say," Brown said. 
"So much of this is motivation." 
</P>
<P>
Johnson, 29, the 1984 Olympic downhill champion, had two disks removed in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
Asked about his future, the typically flip Johnson said, "Who cares? Can I play 
the piano again? I've never been able to do that." 
</P>
<P>
The Troutdale, Ore., resident said he won't know if he can resume racing until 
he begins training. "We'll just have to see how it goes this summer," said 
Johnson. "If I'm able to train a lot and get back in shape, I'm sure it will be 
no problem. But if there are complications along the way and I'm doubting 
myself, I might just hang the boards up." 
</P>
</TEXT>
